Due to internet connectivity issues, Mundelein High School will go to asynchronous learning for the remainder of Monday, August 31. The technology department is working to resolve the issue by this evening. MHS will return to regularly scheduled classes on Tuesday, September 1. Students are responsible to visit their teachers Canvas pages for lessons and assignments. Assignment completion will count as student attendance for the school day.
Tech Campus has not reported any issues. We will notify Tech Campus of our situation. Students will still be responsible for the classwork.

COMMUNITY HOLDS SCHOOL SUPPLY DISTRIBUTION FOR FAMILIES IN NEED
The Mundelein community held a School Supplies Distribution event for area families in need of school supplies to start the new school year. One hundred fifty bags of supplies were distributed to students who attend districts 75, 76 and 120. The community collected supplies and, in addition, the Mundelein Citizens’ Police Academy Alumni Association, the Mundelein Latino Police Academy Alumni Association and the Mundelein Police Department partnered together and made a $750 donation to the drive. Arnold Krinski, president of the Police Academy Alumni, delivered the check to the group last week.
The Black Student Union of MHS assisted in the distribution efforts. They volunteered the evening of August 27. “This event would not have been successful without their support,” said Jamie DiCarlo, assistant superintendent of student services. “The idea for the event came from Veronica Villasenor, community member and District 120 parent,” DiCarlo explained.

MHS TO HOST VIRTUAL COLLEGE PLANNING NIGHT
MHS sets College Planning Night for Seniors
Mundelein High School will host its annual College Planning Night for Seniors in a very different way this year. The event will take place remotely on Tuesday, Sept. 2 in Spanish at 6:30 p.m. and in English at 7:30 p.m.
College representatives from the University of Illinois will provide tips and advice about how seniors can make their applications the best they can be. “This information applies to any student who plans to attend any university,” said Andrea Rusk, college counselor at MHS.
Links to join the presentations will be available in the EVENTS calendar closer to the time of the event. The calendar can also be accessed on the CCRC Virtual College Counseling Classroom

MHS School Community,
It is with great disappointment that I inform you of an incident of a racial slur spoken by a student during our freshman orientation session Friday morning.
While the vast majority of our students were respectful, one student unmuted and spoke a racial slur toward African Americans and other profanity. It was appalling, unacceptable and goes against every core value at Mundelein High School. MHS is on a journey to deconstruct racial injustice so we can better educate our students for the future.
Our deans of students are investigating and will take appropriate action. Incidents of this nature are unsettling and we encourage students to speak with their teachers, counselors and/or other trusted adults.
Again, what transpired this morning was appalling, unacceptable and goes against every core value at Mundelein High School.

Dr. Anthony Kroll, Principal

Hi all,
D75 librarians and I have partnered with Fremont Public Library to bring a virtual author event to Mundelein. Follow the link below to register for the meeting. It is tomorrow, Wed. at 3 pm.
Joelle Charbonneau is popular and timely with her stories written for teens. Her latest, Verify takes place in a not too distant future where the gov't manages information with just 2 media stations and print has been eliminated! My nightmare!

Hope you'll join us or pass on the link to a teen!

Rebecca Plaza, Mundelein High School Library Information Specialist

2020 GRADUATION SET FOR SUNDAY, JULY 12
Mundelein High School will host a “drive-through” Graduation Ceremony at the high school on Sunday, July 12, from 12 noon through 4 p.m. Graduates, in caps and gowns, will be able to exit their vehicles one at a time, cross a balloon arch and walk across a stage, hear their name being read and be able to take a photo with a cut-out of Maverick the Mustang mascot. This will take place at the east entrance to the new building addition that faces the east parking lot (student parking lot).
The east parking lot will be reserved for graduates and their families only. The press may park in the west parking lot (staff lot), or the lot by the swimming pool entrance. A local radio station will provide music and announcements during the event.

ILLINOIS BACK TO SCHOOL INFORMATION RELEASED
The Illinois State Board of Education released a 60-page guidance document for schools regarding the start of the 2020-2021 school year. This guidance provides a clearer picture of what the school year will look like in terms of in-person learning, scheduling, transportation, social distancing, and safety and health measures.
This document was provided to school districts at the same time it was released to the general public. As a result, we kindly ask for your patience as we review the detailed guidance and integrate this information into our District’s return to school plan.
We will continue to communicate our efforts to plan and prepare for the school year with our staff and families and anticipate releasing our return to school plan in July.
Thank you for your patience, understanding, and flexibility as we continue our work in building a plan that prioritizes the health and safety of our students and staff while maintaining a dynamic learning environment.

FOUR SENIORS EARN ROTARY CLUB SCHOLARSHIPS
Four Mundelein High School students have been awarded scholarships by the Rotary Club of Mundelein-Vernon Hills. The four will share the $12,000 scholarship money with three Vernon Hills students.
The Rotary Club of Mundelein-Vernon Hills has awarded more than $255,000 in academic scholarships to area students over the past 10 years.
The recipients from Mundelein High School include Kavana Belagur, Elyna Mellen, Hannah Stanley and MacKenzie Stewart.
“I congratulate these students on their achievements and their commitment to community service,” said Brian Olson, the Club’s scholarship chair. “Each of these talented and dedicated students exemplify Rotary’s motto of Service Above Self,” he explained.
The Rotary Club of Mundelein-Vernon Hills is one of 34,000 Rotary clubs around the world and consists of action-oriented business, professional and community leaders who support important social causes in Lake County and around the world.

SOPHOMORE'S ESSAY CHOSEN AS ONE OF THREE FROM A FIELD OF 2,700!
Mundelein High School sophomore Dempsey Young has been chosen as one of three Finalists in a Fatherhood Essay Contest sponsored by the Illinois Fatherhood Initiative (IFI). She was chosen from a field of more than 2,700 entries. She and her soon-to-be stepfather will be honored at an IFI Fatherhood Dinner scheduled for August 12 at the Union League Club of Chicago.
“She wrote this essay for class earlier this school year about her relationship with her stepdad,” said Angela McLaughlin, who co-taught Young along with Leah Kolcz in an English 2 course.
Dempsey made the first cut from 2,700 to 130 semifinalists and was then chosen as one of the three awardees.

NEWS ABOUT YEARBOOK DISTRIBUTION
Dear MHS Community,
Thank you for your patience as the yearbook staff worked hard to complete the 2019-2020 yearbook via eLearning. A couple of the editors will also continue to work this summer on a one-page insert to cover some of the summer senior events, most importantly the drive-by graduation, for the book.
While we can expect the yearbooks and the inserts to be delivered to the school by early August, we are still working with school administration to figure out the when and how we will get these yearbooks into the hands of the students who ordered them. As more information becomes available, it will be shared with you.
Therefore, we appreciate your continued patience as we work to give you the best yearbook experience possible for an unprecedented school year.

Sincerely,

The Yearbook Staff

post_text:
SENIORS SHARE FINAL THOUGHTS THROUGH CLASS PROJECT
English Teachers Mark Landuyt, Beth Willis, and Sarah Wilson created a short slide presentation for students to create and share as a representation of their memoir, called our Senior Capstone "Yearsbook.” Their Honors English 4 classes spent much of the end of this semester writing their "Senior Capstone Memoir," which in total is five chapters (one for each year of high school and an afterword) and includes narrative, expository, and argumentative writing throughout. Usually, students "present" the themes/messages as a sort of celebration of their memoirs during this final week. Naturally, that would not really be possible during Remote e-Learning. But it still felt wrong to leave their work without a way to celebrate it. Students wrote honestly and thoughtfully about their time at MHS, especially for many the frustration with how their senior year has ended.
https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1G1io0Wh7M0CO_-ta0PXI2Ieq9snZZm4uA_xrN6L_B_U/edit?usp=sharing

CLARIFICATION ON DETAILS OF THE FRIDAY NIGHT SENIOR DRIVE-THRU
Cars will enter MHS at Midlothian Street and flash their headlights to get in!
Students must remain in their cars.
Student cars will be set in queue in junior (stadium) lot until ready for the procession
Cars must go slow but not stop.
There should be no exchange of items between people.
Family members are welcome with their students.
The senior (east) lot is for staff only.
Staff will be outside their cars in the senior (east) lot in chairs at the back of their cars or sitting in the open at the back of their cars or sitting in the driver seat.
Staff would move students along if they try to stop.
Signs and car decorations are encouraged!

Students and Families,

Due to the extension of the Governor’s shelter-in-place order, we will not be retrieving personal items from students’ lockers until a later date. Thank you to those who sent an email to info@d120.org and made a request. We will still make sure you get everything you need, but we will not be gathering items and returning until a future date.

If there is something that you need (inhaler, glasses, medication, wallet) more than a typical personal item, please let us know at info@d120.org and we will make arrangements for you to pick up those items next week.

Thank you for your patience as we navigate through this time. Keep up with your eLearning, and more importantly, take care of yourselves and your loved ones.

STUDENTS, STAFF, ALUMNI, FUTURE MUSTANGS, PARENTS…SHARE YOUR CREATIVE WORK!
Art Instructor Jonathan Pruc is encouraging all members of Mundelein schools, community, Future Mustangs and others to share the creative ways they are coping with the effects of the COVID-19 virus.
“This could include anything from drawing, painting, photography, 3D art, dance, music, family game night, puzzles, arts and crafts, knitting, etc. With more time spent at home, this can be a platform for everyone to share and receive creative inspiration to encourage the exploration and learning process,” he said.
Works are posted on Facebook and Instagram; **submissions should be sent to the Instagram Account for approval**.
https://www.instagram.com/mhsart120/
https://www.facebook.com/MUNDFAA/

post_text:
STUDENTS COLLECT FUNDS FOR BI-WEEKLY LUNCH BOX DELIVERIES
Mundelein High School students from the SALT and Student Leadership groups collected $1,225 to use to help families in need. They collected funds through various means, including at Aldi, wearing protective masks to serve as role models, Students participants included Damia Ali, Ella Brandt, Dillon Blake, Sahil Patel and Jennifer Lopez. The students are so grateful for the community support and are thankful they can help, even if in a small way. The group donated $400 toward this week's food deliveries and will use the remaining funds for the next few week's deliveries. Donations for the project are still appreciated and can be dropped off at The Chapel, at the intersection of Hawley ST and Route 83.

They collected funds through various means, including at Aldi, wearing protective masks to serve as role models, Students participants included Damia Ali, Ella Brandt, Dillon Blake, Sahil Patel and Jennifer Lopez. The students are so grateful for the community support and are thankful they can help, even if in a small way. The group donated $400 toward this week's food deliveries and will use the remaining funds for the next few week's deliveries. Donations for the project are still appreciated and can be dropped off at The Chapel, at the intersection of Hawley ST and Route 83.

post_text:
For their last competition of the season the MHS Show Choirs took part in the Totino-Grace High School event in Fridley, MN, a Minneapolis suburb.
SoundFX, the all-male group, was named first place runner-up in the single gender division while Lights, the all-female group, took the second runner-up spot in the same category. Sound, the mixed gender choir, took seventh place in the Open Class division.
Matthew Callas was once again named Best Male Soloist, the third time this season he has earned that award.
“All of the groups have had an extremely successful season, and are very thankful for the support from the Mundelein community,” said Cory Thompson, who, with Stevee Bellas, directs the vocal music program at MHS.
The next performance for the Choral Department will feature the Honors Concert Choir and Honors Master Singers in a free concert Thursday, April 16 at 7 p.m. at St. Mary of the Annunciation Catholic Church in Fremont.
“This concert is the pinnacle of their year and is an event you don’t want to miss,” Thompson said.
Photos: SoundFX and Matthew Callas

post_text:
MUNDELEIN THEATRE TO PRESENT CHICAGO BEFORE COMPETITION
Mundelein High School Theatre will present this year’s Group Interpretation competition show, Chicago, Thursday and Friday, March 19 and 20 in the MHS Auditorium. Tickets are $5 and may be purchased at the door 20 minutes prior to each performance. The IHSA Sectional Competition will follow at Lake Park High School on Saturday, March 21.
While most people are familiar with the musical version of Chicago, the group interpretation is primarily focused on the Maurine Dallas Watkins original 1926 play as well as her actual Tribune newspaper articles covering Beulah Annan and Belva Gaertner, the real life murderesses who inspired Roxie Hart and Velma Kelly in the musical.
“Like the musical, the play deals with some mature and violent topics in a satirical manner,” said Mark Landuyt who directs the performances.

FREE BAND CONCERT AT MHS MARCH 11
Mundelein High School’s bands will perform in concert Wednesday, March 11 at 7 p.m. in the MHS Auditorium. Admission is free and open to the public.
The event will feature the four concert bands, including the Honors Wind Ensemble, Honors Symphonic Winds, Symphonic Band and Concert Band. The concert will also feature 2019-2020 MHS Concerto Competition runner-up Leila Moon performing Concertino for Clarinet by Carl Maria von Weber.
Other selections to be performed include Illuminations by David Maslanka, Bandology by Eric Osterling, Shenandoah by Omar Thomas, and Symphony No. 1, In Memoriam, Dresden 1945 by Daniel Bukvich.
Jerald Shelato and Andy Sturgeon direct the instrumental music program at MHS.

SENIOR EARNS FULL TUITION SCHOLARSHIP TO TRINITY CHRISTIAN COLLEGE
Mundelein High School Senior, Leslie Osorio, has earned a full tuition scholarship to Trinity Christian College in Palos Heights, IL. Known as a “first gen” student, Osorio is the first person in her family to attend college. The award was presented on Friday, Feb. 28, with her parents, counselors and several of her teachers on hand.
Osorio plans to major in nursing and minor in Spanish. During her years at MHS she has been a member of National Honor Society, Link Crew, Fellowship of Christian Athletes, Medical Club, Puertas and also a member of her church choir.
Photo: Leslie with her parents, Fortino Osorio and Cecilia Merida, and her counselors Jimmy Ku (grades 9-11) and Aracely Lawrence (grade 12).

post_text:
SHOW CHOIRS PLACE IN COMPETITION; PREP FOR UPCOMING CONCERT
Mundelein High School’s three show choirs were on the road again Feb. 15 as they competed at the Naperville North’s Clash of the Sequins event. Lights, the all-female group, was first runner-up in the single gender division and Sound, the mixed choir, made the finals, finishing the day in fifth runner-up position. The MHS Noise Band was also named Best Band.
“The competition drew the best show choirs from around the state of Illinois as well as schools from Wisconsin and Iowa,” said Cory Thompson, who directs the vocal music program along with Stevee Bellas.
The choirs are now preparing for their upcoming free concert Thursday, March 5 at 7 p.m. in the MHS Auditorium. The concert will feature all of the MHS choral ensembles including Chorale, Bella Voce, The Noteables, Honors Concert Choir, Honors Master Singers along with Lights, SoundFX and Sound.
The show choirs will top off their competitive season with a final competition at Totino-Grace High School in Minneapolis March 7.

SHOW CHOIRS CONTINUE TO DOMINATE IN COMPETITION
Fresh off their Jan. 25 victories in Prairie du Sac, Wisconsin, the Mundelein High School show choirs did it again, this time at the Fort Atkinson, WI Showcase.
Lights were named Grand Champions in the Single Gender Division; SoundFX were first runner-up in that division and Sound were named first runner-up overall (of 21 groups competing). Matthew Callas was named Best Male Soloist in Soloist competition while Kira Buckner was named Best Female Vocalist within a show.
Cory Thompson and Stevee Bellas are the vocal music directors at MHS.
The next competition will take place at Naperville North High School Saturday, Feb. 15, for the Clash of the Sequins competition. Tickets are $20 for the entire day of music. SoundFX will compete at 9:45 a.m., Lights at 11:15 a.m. and Sound at 5 p.m.
“All of the competing groups are outstanding show choirs, so it will be a wonderful day of entertainment for the audience,” Thompson said.

GIRLS BASKETBALL TO HOST BREAST CANCER AWARENESS NIGHT
Mundelein High School’s girls basketball team will host a Breast Cancer Awareness Night game against the Stevenson Patriots Friday, Feb. 7. Games are set for 5:30 and 7 p.m.; tickets are $5.
Short-sleeved T-shirts will be on sale during the game for $10 and long-sleeves for $15. All proceeds will benefit the Lynn Sage Foundation.
“Come ‘Pack the House’ and cheer on the Mustangs,” said Greg Dorgan, varsity coach.

CONGRATS TO THE MHS JAZZ ENSEMBLE ON THEIR SELECTION AND PERFORMANCES
The Mundelein High School Jazz Ensemble has returned from their performance and experience at the 2020 Illinois Music Education Conference in Peoria, IL! The students performed a beautiful set of music on Thursday afternoon and celebrated with a steak dinner. "There were so many phenomenal performances at the conference and it was wonderful having Mundelein jazz represented," said Andy Sturgeon, Jazz Ensemble conductor.

NAVY REPRESENTATIVES SPEAK TO STUDENTS ABOUT CAREERS
More than 250 students in physical science and chemistry classes taught by Chris Michalides spent some time on Monday, Jan. 27 with three representatives of the US Navy. The trio spoke about the wide range of career opportunities exist including dolphin trainer. The Navy provides full tuition to any college where a student is accepted and also cash bonuses for completing additional training. This has become an annual event in Michalides' classes.

MUSIC GROUPS STEAL THE SHOW IN OPENING COMPETITION
Mundelein High School’s show choirs started their competition season with a bang and they piled up a number of awards at Sauk Prairie High School in Prairie du Sac, Wisconsin Jan. 25.
Lights, the all-female group, were named Grand Champions in their division while SoundFX, the all-male group, earned Runner-Up status. Noise, the show choir band, was awarded Best Instrumental Ensemble.
Sound, the mixed gender show choir was named first runner-up in the Open Class division.
Two show choir members received top honors as well. Matthew Callas was named Best Male Soloist within a show while Kira Buckner received the Best Female Soloist within a show award.
The groups will next compete at Fort Atkinson, Wisconsin event Saturday, Feb. 8.
Cory Thompson and Stevee Bellas direct the vocal groups while Andy Sturgeon directs the Noise Band.
